    "John T. Carroll": "). Unlike the people of Nazareth, the residents of Capernaum welcome\nJesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` with open arms, yet they, too, eventually set themselves against his mis-\nsion. He must journey to other cities to declare the news of God\u2019s reign.\n31 [Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`] went down to Capernaum, a city in Galilee, and he was teach-\ning the people there on the Sabbath day.a 32 They were astonished at his\nteaching, because his wordsb carried authority.c\n33 Now in the synagogue there was a man who had the spirit of an\nunclean demon, and he began to cry out in a loud voice, 34 \u201cHey!d What\ndo you have to do with us, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` the Nazarene? Did you come to destroy\nus? I know who you are: the Holy One of God!\u201d 35 And Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` rebuked\nhim: \u201cBe silent, and come out of him!\u201d And the demon threw him down in\ntheir midst and came out of him without doing him any harm. 36 Amaze-\nment came upon everyone, and they began to speak with one another:\n\u201cWhat is this message?e For with authority and power he gives orders\nto the unclean spirits, and they come out!\u201d 37 And so a report about him\nspread to every place in that area.\n38 When he got up [and came out] from the synagogue, he entered the\nhouse of Simon. Now Simon\u2019s mother-in-law was suffering with a high\nfever, and they asked [Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`] about her. 39 Standing over her, he rebuked\nthe fever, and it left her. And at once she got up and began to serve them.\n40 As the sun was setting, all who had charge of persons who were sick\nwith various illnesses brought them to [Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`]. And placing his hands on\neach one of them, he healed them.f 41 And demons also went out from many\npeople, shouting, \u201cYou are the Son of God!\u201d And rebuking [them], he\nwould not permit them to speak, because they knew that he was the Christ.\n42 The next day, when he had left [the town], he journeyed to a deserted\nplace. The crowds, though, were searching for him, and they came up to\nhim and tried to keep himg from leaving them. 43 But he told them, \u201cIt is\nnecessary for me to declare the good news of God\u2019s reign to other cities,\ntoo. That\u2019s what I was sent to do.\u201dh\n44 And he was preaching in the synagogues of Judea.i\n118\n[v_Luk_4_14] Luke 4:14\u20139:50\na. The plural \u201cSabbaths\u201d here is to be construed as functionally singular (as in 13:10),\neven though 4:16 employs different phrasing (\u201con the day of [among] the Sabbaths,\u201d\na partitive genitive) to introduce Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 action on a particular Sabbath.\nVerses 31\u201332\nand\nv. 18)\u2014in contrast to the sons and daughters\nof Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]` who populate this part of Luke\u2019s narrative (13:16; 16:24\u201331; 19:9).\nThere is clear precedent, however, for outsiders to Israel enjoying access to\ndivine succor (4:25\u201327; 7:1\u201310; 8:26\u201339). Now, in this liminal space\u2014a border\nzone between Galilee, site of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 productive earlier ministry, and Samaria,\nsite of ministry spurned (9:52\u201356)\u2014the doubly marginalized, liminal character\n344\n[v_Luk_9_51] Luke 9:51\u201319:27\nof a Samaritan leper dares to turn aside from Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 explicit directions, returning\nto the source of his healing.101 Though cast in harsh terms, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 reaction, in\nspeech to observers assumed to be present (\u201cWhere are the nine?\u201d; \u201cnone .\u202f.\u202f.\nexcept this foreigner?\u201d [17:17\u201318]), acknowledges the Samaritan\u2019s response to\nhealing as the fitting one.102\nSo he bids the man, \u201cGet up and journey on,\u201d this time without specifying a\ndestination (\nv. 18), his restored health is an event that\ncalls for public acclamation of the glory of God. Thus this narrative of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019\nhealing act and a Samaritan\u2019s response of faith and grateful praise supplies a",
    "John Trapp": "Against heaven and before thee ] That is, I have not only thee, but the whole heaven for a swift witness against me of mine offences and outbursts. \"The heaven doth declare mine iniquity, and the earth riseth up against me,\" #Job 20:27 .\nVer.\n18. Against heaven and before thee] That is, I have not only thee, but the whole heaven for a swift witness against me of mine offences and outbursts. \"The heaven doth declare mine iniquity, and [v_Job_20_27] the earth riseth up against me,\" #Job 20:",
    "Commentary Vol. 141": "Ft244 --  Pirke Eliezer, c.\n18. Ft245 --  Chambers's Cyclopaedia in the word \u201cLeprosy\u201d.\nFt246 --  T. Bab. Sanhedrin, fol. 52. 2. & Gloss. in ib.\nFt247 --  T. Bab. Bava Metzia, fol. 111. 2. & Gloss. in lb.\nFt248 --  T. Bab. Beracot, fol. 51. 1. & Gloss. in ib. & Bava Bathra, fol. 98.\n1. & Maimon. Hilch. Mecira, c. 17. sect. 6.\n679\nFt249 --  T. Bab. Kiddushin, fol. 22."
